Christopher</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='7049#1245439261'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2009-06-19T19:21:01+00:00">Jun 19, 2009 07:21 PM UTC</time> by <b>Arvind Gopu</b><a class="anchor" name="1245439261">&nbsp;</a></div><pre><font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; 1) Re&#58; Current CRL metric</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; (a) Expired CRLs - Not much one can do ... if a CA lets its CRL expire without releasing a new one. You could try increasing the frequency of &#34;fetch-crl&#34; in your cron. Let me know if you need help with this.</font>

I check with Alain Roy (VDT). Apparently there is currently no clean way to change the frequency at which fetch-crl runs. You will have to edit root&#39;s crontab (crontab -e), and edit the hourly frequency to be more than once a day or what ever it is set to be.

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;(b) Expiring-soon CRLS - Some CAs provide CRLs that expire shortly after .. say 48 hours later. To avoid annoying warnings like that you could try modifying the threshold used to calculate warnings -- I can provide more information if you would like.</font>

Do the following&#58;

echo &#34; --warning-hours &#60;threshold value of your choice&#62;&#34; &#62;&#62; $VDT_LOCATION/osg-rsv/specs/global-specs/cacert-crl-expiry-probe@....
## Re-run configure_osg_rsv or configure-osg.py depending on which option you used to configure RSV
vdt-control --off osg-rsv
vdt-control --on osg-rsv

Cheers,
-ag</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='7049#1245164830'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2009-06-16T15:07:10+00:00">Jun 16, 2009 03:07 PM UTC</time> by <b>john.mora@....</b><a class="anchor" name="1245164830">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>More information on how to accomplish both (a) and (b) is appreciated.

Thank you,
- John

On Tue, Jun 16, 2009 at 8&#58;53 AM, Open Science Grid
FootPrints&#60;osg@....&#62; wrote&#58;
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; [Duplicate message snipped]</font></pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='7049#1245160395'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2009-06-16T13:53:15+00:00">Jun 16, 2009 01:53 PM UTC</time> by <b>Arvind Gopu</b><a class="anchor" name="1245160395">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi John,

There are two issues here&#58;

1) Re&#58; Current CRL metric
(a) Expired CRLs - Not much one can do ... if a CA lets its CRL expire without releasing a new one. You could try increasing the frequency of &#34;fetch-crl&#34; in your cron. Let me know if you need help with this.
(b) Expiring-soon CRLS - Some CAs provide CRLs that expire shortly after .. say 48 hours later. To avoid annoying warnings like that you could try modifying the threshold used to calculate warnings -- I can provide more information if you would like.

2) Second one that is the RSV team&#39;s court&#58; Sites should not be responsible for CA behavior .. ie how often they update their CRLs, etc. This should be the responsibility of the OSG security team. Unfortunately when we released RSVv2 we did not get a reasonable consensus on what this metric should do ... The good news is that a rewritten site-level CRL (and CA) metric are just around the corner ... they are expected to be released in July.

Hope this makes sense.

Cheers,
-ag</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='7049#1245101680'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2009-06-15T21:34:40+00:00">Jun 15, 2009 09:34 PM UTC</time> by <b>Christopher Pipes</b><a class="anchor" name="1245101680">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Arvind,

I am passing this to you as I have no prior knowledge of this subject. I&#39;ll help in
anyway I can.

Thanks,
Christopher</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='7049#1245097634'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2009-06-15T20:27:14+00:00">Jun 15, 2009 08:27 PM UTC</time> by <b>OSG-GOC</b><a class="anchor" name="1245097634">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>GOC -

